  "prompt": "Do anti-money laundering regulations exist?",
  "response": "Yes, anti-money laundering (AML) regulations exist in many countries around the world. These regulations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income. Key aspects of AML regulations typically include:\n\n1. Customer identification and verification requirements\n2. Transaction monitoring\n3. Reporting suspicious activities\n4. Maintaining records of financial transactions\n5. Implementing compliance programs\n6. Imposing penalties for non-compliance\n\nIn the United States, for example, the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the USA PATRIOT Act provide comprehensive AML regulations. Similar regulations exist in the European Union, United Kingdom, and many other countries worldwide.\n\nFinancial institutions like banks, credit unions, and other money services businesses are typically required to implement robust AML compliance programs.",
